00:00:21.010 --> 00:00:22.590
PROFESSOR: So last
time we started

00:00:22.590 --> 00:00:25.620
talking about superfluid helium.

00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:32.070
And we said that the
phase diagram of helium-4,

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:36.710
the isotope that is a boson
has the following interesting

00:00:36.710 --> 00:00:37.700
properties.

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:40.530
First of all, helium
stays a liquid

00:00:40.530 --> 00:00:43.000
all the way down
to 0 temperature

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.990
because of the combinations
of its light mass and heat

00:00:45.990 --> 00:00:47.960
interactions.

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:53.970
And secondly, that [INAUDIBLE]
to cool down helium

00:00:53.970 --> 00:00:57.580
through this process
of evaporated cooling,

00:00:57.580 --> 00:00:59.550
one immediately observes
something interesting

00:00:59.550 --> 00:01:03.200
happening at temperatures
below 2 degrees

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:07.020
Kelvin, where it becomes
this superfluid that

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:10.000
has a number of
interesting properties.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.430
And in particular as
pertaining to viscosity,

00:01:13.430 --> 00:01:15.080
we made two observations.

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:18.400
First of all, you can
make these capillaries--

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:20.880
and I'll show you been
movie in more detail later

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:24.710
on where it flows through
capillaries as if there

00:01:24.710 --> 00:01:28.440
is no resistance
and there is nothing

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:31.010
that sticks to the walls
of the capillaries.

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:33.770
It flows without
viscosity, whereas there

00:01:33.770 --> 00:01:37.190
was this experiment of
Andronikashvili, in which you

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:40.080
had something that
was oscillating

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:44.760
and you were calculating
how much of the helium

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:47.710
was stuck to the plates
of the container.

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:50.920
And the result was
something like this,

00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:58.080
that is there was a decrease
in the amount of fluid

00:01:58.080 --> 00:01:59.460
that is stuck to the plates.

00:01:59.460 --> 00:02:02.705
But it doesn't go
immediately down to 0.

00:02:02.705 --> 00:02:04.780
It has a kind of
form such as this

00:02:04.780 --> 00:02:10.560
that I will draw more
clearly now and explain.

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:16.250
So what we did last time was
to note that people observed

00:02:16.250 --> 00:02:17.860
that there were
some similarities

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:20.010
between this
superfluid transition

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:22.640
and Bose-Einstein condensation.

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:26.360
But what I would
like to highlight

00:02:26.360 --> 00:02:28.200
in the beginning
of this lecture is

00:02:28.200 --> 00:02:32.450
that there are also very
important differences.

00:02:32.450 --> 00:02:40.310
So let's think about
these distinctions

00:02:40.310 --> 00:02:48.126
between Bose-Einstein condensate
add the superfluid helium.

00:02:58.690 --> 00:03:05.120
One set of things we would
like to take from the picture

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:12.660
that I have over there, which
is diffraction of the fluid that

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:15.370
is stuck to the plates
and in some sense

00:03:15.370 --> 00:03:19.030
behaves like a normal fluid.

00:03:19.030 --> 00:03:24.050
Now let me make the analogy
to Bose-Einstein condensation.

00:03:24.050 --> 00:03:27.400
You know that in the
Bose-Einstein condensation

00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:32.260
there was also this phenomenon
that there was a separation

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:36.230
into two parts of
the total density.

00:03:36.230 --> 00:03:39.650
And be regarded as a
function of temperature

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:45.750
some part of the density as
belonging to the normal state.

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:50.840
So when you are above
Tc of n, everything

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.860
is essentially normal.

00:03:53.860 --> 00:04:02.600
And then what happens is
that when you hit Tc of n

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:07.530
you can no longer put
all of the particles

00:04:07.530 --> 00:04:11.320
that you have in
the excited states.

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:13.870
So the fraction that goes
in the excited states

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:20.590
goes down and eventually
goes to 0 at 0 temperature.

00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:31.770
And essentially, this would
be the reverse of the curve

00:04:31.770 --> 00:04:34.180
that we have in that
figure over there.

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:39.610
Basically, there's
a portion that

00:04:39.610 --> 00:04:42.940
would be the normal part that
would be looking like this.

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:52.430
Now, the way that we
obtained this result

00:04:52.430 --> 00:04:54.860
was that basically there
was a fraction that

00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:57.100
was in the normal state.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.040
The part that was
excited was described

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:05.500
by this simple formula that was
g over lambda cubed [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:07.410
of 3/2.

00:05:07.410 --> 00:05:10.960
So it went to 0 as T to the 3/2.

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:12.990
So basically, the
proportionality

00:05:12.990 --> 00:05:16.040
here is T to the 3/2.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:17.950
And then basically,
the curve would

00:05:17.950 --> 00:05:22.270
come down here and
go to 0 linearly.

00:05:22.270 --> 00:05:26.260
Now what is shown
in the experiment

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:30.000
is that the curve
actually goes to 0

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.600
in a much more sharp fashion.

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:40.250
And actually, when people try
to fit a curve through this,

00:05:40.250 --> 00:05:44.010
the curve looks something like
Tc minus T to the 2/3 over.

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:54.140
But also it goes to 0 much
more rapidly than the curve

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:57.100
that we have for
Bose-Einstein condensation.

00:05:57.100 --> 00:05:59.900
Indeed, it goes through
0 proportionately to T

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:02.650
to the fourth.

00:06:02.650 --> 00:06:06.100
And so that's something that we
need to understand and explain.

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:18.070
Now all of the properties of
the Bose-Einstein condensate

00:06:18.070 --> 00:06:21.840
was very easy to
describe once we realized

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:26.010
that all of the things that
correspond to excitation,

00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:28.500
such as the energy,
heat capacity,

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:32.350
pressure, come from
this fraction that

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:35.210
is in the excited state.

00:06:35.210 --> 00:06:39.010
And we can calculate,
say, the contribution

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:42.060
to energy heat
capacity, et cetera.

00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:45.730
And in particular, if we look
at the behavior of the heat

00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:50.400
capacity as a function
of temperature,

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:57.240
for this Bose-Einstein
condensate, the behavior

00:06:57.240 --> 00:07:01.090
that we had was that again
simply at low temperatures

00:07:01.090 --> 00:07:08.000
it was going proportionately
to T to the 3/2,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.160
because this was the number
of excitations that you had.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:15.090
So these two T to the
3/2 are very much related

00:07:15.090 --> 00:07:16.960
to each other.

00:07:16.960 --> 00:07:22.300
And then this curve would
basically go along its way

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:26.450
until it hit Tc of
n at some point.

00:07:26.450 --> 00:07:28.930
And we separately
calculated the behavior

00:07:28.930 --> 00:07:30.640
coming from high temperatures.

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:33.140
And the behavior from
high temperatures

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:35.480
would start with
the classical result

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:39.500
that the heat capacity
is 3/2 per particle

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:42.800
due to the kinetic energy that
you can put in these things.

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:46.327
And then it would rise, and it
would then join this curve over

00:07:46.327 --> 00:07:49.189
here.

00:07:49.189 --> 00:07:54.760
Now when you look at the
actual heat capacity,

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:57.380
indeed the shape up
the heat capacity

00:07:57.380 --> 00:08:01.370
is the thing that gives this
transition the name of a lambda

00:08:01.370 --> 00:08:02.180
transition.

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:03.805
It kind of looks like a lambda.

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:13.390
And at Tc there are
divergences approaching

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:17.600
from the two sides that
behave like the log.

00:08:24.450 --> 00:08:27.680
And again more
importantly, what we

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:30.770
find is that at
0 temperature, it

00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:34.730
doesn't go through 0, the
heat capacity as T to the 3/2,

00:08:34.730 --> 00:08:38.909
but rather as T to
the third power.

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:46.060
So the red curve
corresponds to superfluid,

00:08:46.060 --> 00:08:51.710
the green curve corresponds
to Bose-Einstein condensate.

00:08:51.710 --> 00:08:56.550
And so they're clearly
different from each other.

00:08:56.550 --> 00:09:00.980
So that's what we would
like you to understand.

00:09:00.980 --> 00:09:07.010
Well the thing that is easiest
to understand and figure out

00:09:07.010 --> 00:09:10.780
is the difference between
these heat capacities.

00:09:10.780 --> 00:09:13.510
And the reason for that
is that we had already

00:09:13.510 --> 00:09:17.400
seen a form that was of
the heat capacity that

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:18.600
behaved like T cubed.

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:23.050
That was when we were looking
at phonons in a solid.

00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:25.880
So let's remind
you why was it that

00:09:25.880 --> 00:09:28.740
for the Bose-Einstein
condensate we

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:34.010
were getting this T
to the 3/2 behavior?

00:09:34.010 --> 00:09:38.520
The reason for that was that
the various excitations,

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:46.612
I could plot as a function
of k, or p, which is h bar k.

00:09:46.612 --> 00:09:49.450
They're very much
related to each other.

00:09:49.450 --> 00:09:53.890
And for the
Bose-Einstein condensate,

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:58.310
the form was simply
a parabola, which

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:03.144
is this p squared over
2 mass of the helium.

00:10:03.144 --> 00:10:06.330
Let's say, assuming that
what we are dealing with

00:10:06.330 --> 00:10:12.620
is non-interacting particles
with mass of helium.

00:10:12.620 --> 00:10:17.390
And this parabolic
curve essentially

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:28.050
told us that various quantities
behave as T to the 3/2.

00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:32.920
Roughly, the idea is that
at some temperature that

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:37.520
has energy of the order
of kT, you figure out

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:41.800
how far you have excited things.

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:45.000
And since this
form is a parabola,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:48.700
the typical p is going to
scale like T to the 1/2.

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:55.810
You have a volume in three
dimensions in p space.

00:10:55.810 --> 00:10:59.110
If the radius goes
like T to the 1/2,

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:02.030
the volume goes
like T to the 3/2.

00:11:02.030 --> 00:11:04.880
That's why you have all kinds
of excitations such as this.

00:11:08.150 --> 00:11:13.090
And the reason for the
Bose-Einstein condensation

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:19.790
was that you would start to fill
out all of these excitations.

00:11:19.790 --> 00:11:25.430
And when you were adding all
of the mean occupation numbers,

00:11:25.430 --> 00:11:27.783
the answer was not
coming up all the way

00:11:27.783 --> 00:11:29.800
to the total number
of particles.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:32.400
So then you have to put
an excess at p close

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.880
to 0, which corresponds to the
ground state of this system.

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:41.090
Now of course when
you look at helium,

00:11:41.090 --> 00:11:44.310
helium molecules, helium
atoms have the interactions

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:46.440
between them that we discussed.

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:50.130
In particular, you can't really
put them on top of each other.

00:11:50.130 --> 00:11:53.150
There is a hard exclusion
when you bring things

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:55.460
close to each other.

00:11:55.460 --> 00:11:58.470
So the ground
state of the system

00:11:58.470 --> 00:12:00.760
must look very different
from the ground state

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:04.180
of the Bose-Einstein condensate
in which the particles freely

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:08.000
occupy the entire box.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.030
So there is a very
difficult story

00:12:12.030 --> 00:12:15.020
associated with
figuring out what

00:12:15.020 --> 00:12:18.930
the ground state of this
combination of interacting

00:12:18.930 --> 00:12:22.880
particles that make
up liquid helium is.

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:23.930
What is the behavior?

00:12:23.930 --> 00:12:26.260
What's the many-body wave
function at 0 temperature?

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:34.630
Now as we see here, in order
to understand the heat capacity

00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:37.130
we really don't
need to know what

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:40.060
is happening at
the ground state.

00:12:40.060 --> 00:12:43.350
What we need to know in
order to find heat capacity

00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:47.170
is how to put more energy in the
system above the ground state.

00:12:47.170 --> 00:12:51.090
So we need to know
something about excitations.

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:54.930
And so that's the
perspective that Landau took.

00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:58.900
Landau said, well, this is
the spectrum of excitations

00:12:58.900 --> 00:13:03.470
if you had [? plain ?] particles
without any interactions.

00:13:03.470 --> 00:13:06.120
Let's imagine what
happens if we gradually

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:08.220
tune in the interactions,
the particles

00:13:08.220 --> 00:13:10.960
start to repel each
other, et cetera.

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:13.120
This non-interacting
ground state

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:16.480
that we had in which the
particles were uniformly

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:18.590
distributed across
the system will

00:13:18.590 --> 00:13:22.910
evolve into some complicated
ground state I don't know.

00:13:22.910 --> 00:13:25.210
And then, presumably
there would be a spectrum

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:30.260
of excitations around
that ground state.

00:13:30.260 --> 00:13:34.760
Now the excitations around
the non-interacting ground

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:39.250
state we can label by
this momentum peak.

00:13:39.250 --> 00:13:40.990
And it kind of
makes sense that we

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:45.080
should be able to have a
singular label for excitations

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:48.850
around the ground state of
these interacting particles.

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:50.550
And this is where
you sort of needed

00:13:50.550 --> 00:13:53.330
a little bit of Landau's
type of insight.

00:13:53.330 --> 00:13:55.590
He said, well,
presumably what you

00:13:55.590 --> 00:13:59.770
do when you have
excitations of momentum p

00:13:59.770 --> 00:14:03.940
is to distort the wave
function in a manner that

00:14:03.940 --> 00:14:10.330
is consistent with having these
kind of excitations of momentum

00:14:10.330 --> 00:14:11.580
p.

00:14:11.580 --> 00:14:14.680
And he said, well
we typically know

00:14:14.680 --> 00:14:17.990
that if you have
a fluid or a solid

00:14:17.990 --> 00:14:21.850
and we want to impart some
momentum above the ground

00:14:21.850 --> 00:14:24.870
state, if will go in
the form of phonons.

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:28.870
These are distortions in
which the density will

00:14:28.870 --> 00:14:35.060
vary in some sinusoidal or
cosine way across the system.

00:14:35.060 --> 00:14:37.920
So he said that maybe
what is happening

00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:40.370
is that for these
excitations you

00:14:40.370 --> 00:14:43.730
have to take what ever this
interacting ground state is--

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:47.590
which we don't know and
can't write that down--

00:14:47.590 --> 00:14:49.900
but hope that
excitations around it

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:52.950
correspond to these
distortions in density.

00:14:52.950 --> 00:14:56.410
And that by analogy with
what happens for fluids,

00:14:56.410 --> 00:15:01.350
that the spectrum of excitations
will then become a linear.

00:15:01.350 --> 00:15:04.240
You would have something
like a sound wave

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:07.060
that you would have in
a liquid or a solid.

00:15:07.060 --> 00:15:14.290
So if you do this, if you
have a linear spectrum

00:15:14.290 --> 00:15:16.895
then we can see what happen.

00:15:16.895 --> 00:15:21.540
For a particular energy
of the order of kT,

00:15:21.540 --> 00:15:24.670
we will go here,
occupied momenta that

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:27.160
would be of the order
of kT over H bar.

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:35.560
The number of excitations would
be something like this cubed,

00:15:35.560 --> 00:15:37.300
and so you would
imagine that you

00:15:37.300 --> 00:15:41.000
would get a heat capacity that
is proportional to this times

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:42.870
kB.

00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:45.570
And if you do things
correctly, like really

00:15:45.570 --> 00:15:47.840
for the case of
phonons or photons,

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:52.010
you can even figure out what
the numerical prefactor is here.

00:15:52.010 --> 00:15:56.240
And there's a velocity
here because this curve

00:15:56.240 --> 00:15:59.280
goes like H bar vP.

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:09.010
So then you can
compare what you have

00:16:09.010 --> 00:16:15.330
over here with the coefficient
of the T cubed over here,

00:16:15.330 --> 00:16:19.140
and you could even figure
out what this velocity is.

00:16:19.140 --> 00:16:23.030
And it turns out to be of the
order of 240 meters per second.

00:16:27.640 --> 00:16:31.450
A typical sound wave that
you would have in a fluid.

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:35.390
So that's kind of
a reasonable thing.

00:16:35.390 --> 00:16:38.700
Now of course, when you go
to higher and higher momenta,

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:41.420
it corresponds to essentially
shorter and shorter

00:16:41.420 --> 00:16:42.520
wavelengths.

00:16:42.520 --> 00:16:44.880
You expect that when
you get wavelengths

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:49.860
that is of the order of
the interatomic spacing,

00:16:49.860 --> 00:16:52.670
then the interactions become
less and less important.

00:16:52.670 --> 00:16:55.080
You have particles
rattling in a cage

00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:57.230
that is set up by
everybody else.

00:16:57.230 --> 00:17:00.320
And then you should regain
this kind of spectrum

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:03.120
at high values of momentum.

00:17:03.120 --> 00:17:06.920
And so what Landau
did was he basically

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:10.270
joined these things
together and posed

00:17:10.270 --> 00:17:14.760
that there is a spectrum
such as this that

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:17.310
has what is called
a phonon part, which

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:24.359
is this linear part where
energy goes like H bar,

00:17:24.359 --> 00:17:30.290
like the velocity
times the momentum.

00:17:30.290 --> 00:17:35.010
And it has a part that in
the vicinity of this point,

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:37.930
you can expand parabolically.

00:17:37.930 --> 00:17:38.960
And it's called rotons.

00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:46.690
There is a gap
delta, and then H bar

00:17:46.690 --> 00:17:52.390
squared over 2, some effective
mass, k minus k0 squared.

00:17:54.970 --> 00:17:58.110
This k0 turns out to
be roughly of the order

