00:27:24.580 --> 00:27:35.100
I wrote a statement that
the BEC is not superfluid.

00:27:40.310 --> 00:27:44.110
And what that really
means is that it

00:27:44.110 --> 00:27:48.646
has too many excitations,
low energy excitations.

00:27:56.410 --> 00:27:59.630
So imagine the
following, that maybe we

00:27:59.630 --> 00:28:03.650
have a container-- I don't
know, maybe we have a tube--

00:28:03.650 --> 00:28:13.480
and we have our superfluid going
through this with velocity v

00:28:13.480 --> 00:28:15.390
sub s.

00:28:15.390 --> 00:28:21.660
We want it to maintain that
velocity without experiencing

00:28:21.660 --> 00:28:23.870
friction, which it
seems to do in going

00:28:23.870 --> 00:28:25.050
through these capillaries.

00:28:25.050 --> 00:28:29.580
You don't have to push it, it
seems to be going by itself.

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:36.480
And so the question is,
can any of these pictures

00:28:36.480 --> 00:28:42.230
that we drew for excitations
be consistent with this?

00:28:42.230 --> 00:28:45.690
Now, why am I talking about
excitations and consistency

00:28:45.690 --> 00:28:47.810
with superfluid?

00:28:47.810 --> 00:28:51.440
Because what can
happen in principle

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:57.190
is that within your system,
you can spontaneously

00:28:57.190 --> 00:29:00.120
generate some excitation.

00:29:00.120 --> 00:29:04.120
This excitation will
have some momentum p

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:08.410
and some energy epsilon of p.

00:29:08.410 --> 00:29:13.500
And if you spontaneously can
create these excitations that

00:29:13.500 --> 00:29:19.310
would take away energy from this
kinetic energy of the flowing

00:29:19.310 --> 00:29:23.950
superfluid, gradually the
superfluid will slow down.

00:29:23.950 --> 00:29:27.420
Its energy will be
dissipated and the superfluid

00:29:27.420 --> 00:29:29.997
itself will heat up
because you generated

00:29:29.997 --> 00:29:31.080
these excitations with it.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:38.690
So let's see what happens.

00:29:38.690 --> 00:29:42.750
If I were to create
such an excitation,

00:29:42.750 --> 00:29:51.320
actually I have to worry
about momentum conservation

00:29:51.320 --> 00:29:56.120
because I created something
that carried momentum p.

00:29:56.120 --> 00:30:04.690
Now initially, let's say
that this whole entity, all

00:30:04.690 --> 00:30:08.330
of the fluid that are
superflowing with velocity Vs

00:30:08.330 --> 00:30:13.055
have mass M. So the initial
momentum would be MVs.

00:30:16.280 --> 00:30:21.280
Now, I created some
excitation that

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:24.970
is carrying away
some momentum p.

00:30:24.970 --> 00:30:28.740
So the only thing that
can ensure this happens

00:30:28.740 --> 00:30:32.510
is that I have to
slightly change

00:30:32.510 --> 00:30:34.285
the velocity of the fluid.

00:30:37.240 --> 00:30:40.425
Now this change in
velocity is infinitesimal.

00:30:40.425 --> 00:30:48.470
It is Vs minus p
divided by M. M is huge,

00:30:48.470 --> 00:30:53.292
so why bother
thinking about this?

00:30:53.292 --> 00:30:57.040
Well, let's see what
the change in energy is.

00:31:02.250 --> 00:31:07.160
Delta E. Let's say, well,
you created this excitation

00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:09.280
so you have energy epsilon of p.

00:31:12.310 --> 00:31:15.295
But I say, in
addition to that there

00:31:15.295 --> 00:31:20.500
is a change in the kinetic
energy of the superfluid.

00:31:20.500 --> 00:31:23.830
I'm now moving at
Vs prime squared,

00:31:23.830 --> 00:31:28.130
whereas initially when this
excitation was not present,

00:31:28.130 --> 00:31:32.650
I was moving at Vs.

00:31:32.650 --> 00:31:36.300
And so what do you have here?

00:31:36.300 --> 00:31:44.566
We have epsilon of p, M
over 2 Vs minus p over M,

00:31:44.566 --> 00:31:49.920
this infinitesimal change
in velocity squared minus M

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:53.760
over 2 Vs squared.

00:31:53.760 --> 00:31:56.830
We can see that the leading
order of the kinetic energy

00:31:56.830 --> 00:32:01.780
goes away, but that there
is a cross term here

00:32:01.780 --> 00:32:05.660
in which the M contribution--
the contribution of the mass--

00:32:05.660 --> 00:32:07.460
goes away.

00:32:07.460 --> 00:32:15.140
And so the change in energy is
actually something like this.

00:32:18.020 --> 00:32:25.330
So if I had a system that
when stationary, the energy

00:32:25.330 --> 00:32:30.830
to create an excitation of
momentum p was epsilon of p,

00:32:30.830 --> 00:32:35.960
when I put that in a frame that
is moving with some velocity

00:32:35.960 --> 00:32:40.250
Vs, you have the
ability to borrow

00:32:40.250 --> 00:32:45.040
some of that kinetic energy
and the excitation energy

00:32:45.040 --> 00:32:47.045
goes down by this amount.

00:32:58.610 --> 00:33:07.330
So what happens if I take
the Bose-Einstein type

00:33:07.330 --> 00:33:10.810
of excitation spectrum
that is p squared over 2M

00:33:10.810 --> 00:33:15.860
and then subtract
a v dot p from it?

00:33:15.860 --> 00:33:20.520
Essentially there is a
linear subtraction going on,

00:33:20.520 --> 00:33:24.870
and I would get a
curve such as this.

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:28.630
So I probably exaggerated
this by a lot.

00:33:28.630 --> 00:33:31.150
I shouldn't have
subtracted so much.

00:33:31.150 --> 00:33:37.590
Let me actually not
subject so much,

00:33:37.590 --> 00:33:40.260
because we don't want to go
all the way in that range.

00:33:45.860 --> 00:33:50.590
But you can see that there
is a range of momenta where

00:33:50.590 --> 00:33:56.710
you would spontaneously gain
energy by creating excitations.

00:33:56.710 --> 00:34:00.630
If the spectrum was
initially p squared over 2M,

00:34:00.630 --> 00:34:05.430
basically you just have too
many low energy excitations.

00:34:05.430 --> 00:34:07.960
As soon as you
start moving it, you

00:34:07.960 --> 00:34:11.280
will spontaneously
excite these things.

00:34:11.280 --> 00:34:14.080
Even if you were initially
at 0 temperature,

00:34:14.080 --> 00:34:18.340
these phonon excitations
would be created spontaneously

00:34:18.340 --> 00:34:19.159
in your system.

00:34:19.159 --> 00:34:20.840
They would move
all over the place.

00:34:20.840 --> 00:34:22.610
They would heat up your system.

00:34:22.610 --> 00:34:25.800
There is no way
that you can pass

00:34:25.800 --> 00:34:28.889
the Bose-Einstein
condensate-- actually,

00:34:28.889 --> 00:34:32.350
there's no way that you can even
move it without losing energy.

00:34:35.300 --> 00:34:38.900
But you can see that
this red curve does not

00:34:38.900 --> 00:34:40.830
have that difficulty.

00:34:40.830 --> 00:34:44.580
If I were to shift this curve
by an amount that is linear,

00:34:44.580 --> 00:34:45.520
what do I get?

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:47.202
I will get something like this.

00:34:53.880 --> 00:35:00.030
So the Landau spectrum
is perfectly fine

00:35:00.030 --> 00:35:04.980
as far as excitations
is concerned.

00:35:04.980 --> 00:35:11.010
At zero temperature, even if the
whole fluid is moving then it

00:35:11.010 --> 00:35:14.440
cannot spontaneously
create excitations,

00:35:14.440 --> 00:35:17.490
because you would increase
energy of the system.

00:35:20.230 --> 00:35:22.530
So there's this difference.

00:35:22.530 --> 00:35:25.430
Ultimately, you would
say that the first time

00:35:25.430 --> 00:35:32.830
you would get excitation is
if you move it fast enough

00:35:32.830 --> 00:35:36.690
so that some portion of
this curve goes to 0.

00:35:36.690 --> 00:35:39.890
And indeed, if you were
to try to stir or move

00:35:39.890 --> 00:35:43.140
a superfluid fast
enough, there's

00:35:43.140 --> 00:35:45.240
a velocity at which
it breaks down,

00:35:45.240 --> 00:35:47.860
it stops being a superfluid.

00:35:47.860 --> 00:35:52.040
But it turns out that that
velocity is much, much smaller

00:35:52.040 --> 00:35:56.430
than you would predict based on
this roton spectrum going down.

00:35:56.430 --> 00:35:59.530
There are some other
many body excitations

00:35:59.530 --> 00:36:04.830
that come before and cause
