helium II is clearly visible.

00:50:36.610 --> 00:50:39.830
We will show it to you
later in this film.

00:50:39.830 --> 00:50:44.720
The two liquids behave nothing
like any other known liquid,

00:50:44.720 --> 00:50:48.620
although it could be said that
helium I, the warmer phase,

00:50:48.620 --> 00:50:52.140
approximates the behavior
of common liquids.

00:50:52.140 --> 00:50:55.620
But it is helium II,
the colder phase,

00:50:55.620 --> 00:50:57.690
which is truly different.

00:50:57.690 --> 00:51:01.676
Because of this, it is
called a superfluid.

00:51:01.676 --> 00:51:04.730
The temperatures involved when
working with liquid helium

00:51:04.730 --> 00:51:06.730
are quite low.

00:51:06.730 --> 00:51:10.154
Helium boils at
4.2 degrees Kelvin

00:51:10.154 --> 00:51:12.850
under conditions of
atmospheric pressure.

00:51:12.850 --> 00:51:17.400
And the lambda point lies
at roughly 2.2 degrees.

00:51:17.400 --> 00:51:21.810
Note that this
corresponds to minus 269

00:51:21.810 --> 00:51:26.514
and minus 271
degrees centigrade.

00:51:26.514 --> 00:51:29.390
The properties of liquid
helium that I have just

00:51:29.390 --> 00:51:31.738
been telling you about
are characteristic

00:51:31.738 --> 00:51:36.202
of the heavy isotope
if helium, helium-4.

00:51:36.202 --> 00:51:40.178
The element occurs in the
form of two stable isotopes.

00:51:40.178 --> 00:51:43.330
[INAUDIBLE] The second
and lighter one,

00:51:43.330 --> 00:51:46.620
helium-3, is very rare.

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:51.738
Its abundance is only
about 1 part of 10 million.

00:51:51.738 --> 00:51:55.126
Pure liquid helium-3
is the subject

00:51:55.126 --> 00:51:57.950
of intensive study
at the present time,

00:51:57.950 --> 00:52:02.690
but so far no second
superfluid liquid phase

00:52:02.690 --> 00:52:04.868
