containers.

00:52:12.980 --> 00:52:15.045
The dewar meets
our requirements.

00:52:15.045 --> 00:52:17.620
The word "dewar" is
a scientific name

00:52:17.620 --> 00:52:19.758
given to a double-walled
vessel with the space

00:52:19.758 --> 00:52:22.500
between the walls evacuated.

00:52:22.500 --> 00:52:24.000
When these dewars
are made of glass,

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:26.800
the surface of this
inner space is usually

00:52:26.800 --> 00:52:30.045
filtered to cut down heat
transfer by radiation.

00:52:30.045 --> 00:52:33.920
However, our dewars will
have to be transparent

00:52:33.920 --> 00:52:37.280
so that we can look at
what's going on inside.

00:52:37.280 --> 00:52:40.420
Now, liquid helium is commonly
stored in double dewars.

00:52:40.420 --> 00:52:44.035
The design is quite
simple, just put one

00:52:44.035 --> 00:52:49.676
inside the other like this.

00:52:49.676 --> 00:52:52.360
In the inner dewar, we
put the liquid helium,

00:52:52.360 --> 00:52:54.820
and in the space between
the inner and outer dewar,

00:52:54.820 --> 00:52:57.240
we maintain a supply
of liquid air.

00:53:00.300 --> 00:53:02.955
Here is a double dewar
exactly like the one

00:53:02.955 --> 00:53:07.530
we will be using in our
demonstration experiment.

00:53:07.530 --> 00:53:10.700
The inner dewar is filled
with liquid helium.

00:53:10.700 --> 00:53:12.910
The outer dewar
contains liquid air.

00:53:16.530 --> 00:53:19.450
The normal boiling
temperature of liquid air

00:53:19.450 --> 00:53:23.740
is about 80 degrees
Kelvin, 75 or more degrees

00:53:23.740 --> 00:53:26.190
hotter than liquid helium.

00:53:26.190 --> 00:53:28.620
The purpose of the
liquid air is twofold.

00:53:31.710 --> 00:53:34.450
First, we put the liquid air
in the outer dewar well ahead

00:53:34.450 --> 00:53:37.810
of putting liquid helium
in the inner dewar.

00:53:37.810 --> 00:53:42.003
In this way, the inner
dewar is pre-cooled.

00:53:42.003 --> 00:53:44.861
Secondly, we maintain
a supply of liquid air

00:53:44.861 --> 00:53:47.240
in the outer dewar
because it provides

00:53:47.240 --> 00:53:49.910
an additional
[INAUDIBLE] of insulation

00:53:49.910 --> 00:53:53.010
now that the liquid helium
is in the inner dewar.

00:53:53.010 --> 00:53:55.480
The [INAUDIBLE] liquid
air attests to the fact

00:53:55.480 --> 00:53:57.510
that it is absorbing
some of the heat which

00:53:57.510 --> 00:53:58.510
enters the double dewar.

00:54:01.410 --> 00:54:03.850
Even with the boiling
of the liquid air,

00:54:03.850 --> 00:54:06.690
the liquid helium
is clearly visible.

00:54:06.690 --> 00:54:09.140
Later, we will use
liquid air cooled

00:54:09.140 --> 00:54:12.228
below its boiling temperature
to reduce or eliminate

00:54:12.228 --> 00:54:13.811
the air bubbles for
better visibility.

00:54:17.870 --> 00:54:20.050
Now the liquid
air is cooled down

00:54:20.050 --> 00:54:22.540
and we have eliminated boiling.

00:54:22.540 --> 00:54:25.340
The smaller bubbles of
the boiling liquid helium

00:54:25.340 --> 00:54:27.424
are clearly visible.

00:54:27.424 --> 00:54:32.210
The cover over the inner dewar
has a port, at present open.

00:54:32.210 --> 00:54:35.750
The liquid helium is at
atmospheric pressure,

00:54:35.750 --> 00:54:39.200
so its temperature is
4.2 degrees Kelvin.

00:54:43.200 --> 00:54:45.546
In other words, what
we have in here now

00:54:45.546 --> 00:54:49.800
is liquid helium one, the
warmer of the two phases.

00:54:49.800 --> 00:54:53.740
Before we cool it down to take
a look at the superfluid phase,

00:54:53.740 --> 00:54:57.710
I want to dwell greatly on the
properties of helium I. I've

00:54:57.710 --> 00:55:00.665
told you before
that even helium I

00:55:00.665 --> 00:55:04.361
is different from
the normal liquids.

00:55:04.361 --> 00:55:06.610
The distance between neighboring
atoms and this liquid

00:55:06.610 --> 00:55:08.186
is quite large.

00:55:08.186 --> 00:55:10.150
The atoms are not
as closely packed

00:55:10.150 --> 00:55:11.700
as in the classical liquids.

00:55:11.700 --> 00:55:14.890
The reason for this
is quantum mechanics.

00:55:14.890 --> 00:55:17.700
The zero point energy is
relatively more important

00:55:17.700 --> 00:55:19.270
here than in any other liquid.

00:55:21.817 --> 00:55:23.275
As a consequence,
liquid helium has

00:55:23.275 --> 00:55:29.460
a very low mass density, only
about 13% the density of water,

00:55:29.460 --> 00:55:31.430
and a very low optical density.

00:55:31.430 --> 00:55:35.455
The index of refraction
is quite close to 1.

00:55:35.455 --> 00:55:38.510
This makes its surface hard
to see with the naked eye

00:55:38.510 --> 00:55:42.160
under ordinary
lighting conditions.

00:55:42.160 --> 00:55:44.434
You are no doubt
familiar with the fact

00:55:44.434 --> 00:55:49.150
that the helium atom has
closed shell atomic structure.

00:55:49.150 --> 00:55:52.500
This explains why helium is
a chemically inert element.

00:55:52.500 --> 00:55:55.820
It also accounts for the fact
that the force of attraction

00:55:55.820 --> 00:55:58.905
between neighboring helium
atoms, the so-called van der

00:55:58.905 --> 00:56:02.760
Waals force, is small.

00:56:02.760 --> 00:56:05.580
It takes little energy to
pull two helium atoms apart,

00:56:05.580 --> 00:56:10.170
as for example in evaporation.

00:56:10.170 --> 00:56:12.550
This gives liquid helium
a better small latent

00:56:12.550 --> 00:56:14.660
heat of vaporization.

00:56:14.660 --> 00:56:18.242
Only five calories are
needed to evaporate one gram.

00:56:18.242 --> 00:56:21.900
Compare this with water,
where evaporation requires

00:56:21.900 --> 00:56:24.105
between 500 and 600
calories per gram.

00:56:26.780 --> 00:56:30.745
The low van der Waals force
combined with a large zero

00:56:30.745 --> 00:56:34.200
point energy also accounts for
the fact that liquid helium

00:56:34.200 --> 00:56:38.150
does not freeze, cannot
be solidified at ordinary

00:56:38.150 --> 00:56:41.490
pressure, no matter
how far we cool it.

00:56:41.490 --> 00:56:44.700
However, liquid helium has been
solidified at high pressure.

00:56:47.450 --> 00:56:51.465
The liquid helium in the
dewar is at 4,2 degrees.

00:56:51.465 --> 00:56:54.720
We now want to cool it
down to the lambda point

00:56:54.720 --> 00:56:58.396
and show you the transition
to the [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:58.396 --> 00:57:02.132
Our method will be
cooling by evaporation

00:57:02.132 --> 00:57:04.562
using a vacuum pump.

00:57:04.562 --> 00:57:09.960
Now, the lambda point lies at
2.2 degrees, only 2 degrees

00:57:09.960 --> 00:57:14.500
colder than the [INAUDIBLE]
temperature of the liquid.

00:57:14.500 --> 00:57:17.020
What's more, not
very much heat has

00:57:17.020 --> 00:57:19.105
been removed from
the liquid helium

00:57:19.105 --> 00:57:22.455
now in the dewar to bring
it to the lambda point.

00:57:22.455 --> 00:57:27.305
It amounts to only
about 250 calories.

00:57:27.305 --> 00:57:31.013
Nevertheless, don't get the
idea that this cooling process

00:57:31.013 --> 00:57:32.456
is easy.

00:57:32.456 --> 00:57:35.830
On the contrary,
it's quite difficult.

00:57:35.830 --> 00:57:39.240
More than 1/3 of the liquid
helium now in the dewar

00:57:39.240 --> 00:57:41.790
has to be knocked
away in vapor form

00:57:41.790 --> 00:57:46.830
before we can get what remains
behind to the lambda point.

00:57:46.830 --> 00:57:49.763
That requires an
awful lot of pumping

00:57:49.763 --> 00:57:54.020
and explains why we use this
large and powerful vacuum

00:57:54.020 --> 00:57:55.510
pump over here.

00:58:00.812 --> 00:58:03.080
Even with this pump,
the cooling process

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:04.960
takes a considerable
amount of time.

00:59:09.272 --> 00:59:11.268
Let me explain why
it is so difficult

00:59:11.268 --> 00:59:14.262
to cool liquid helium
to the lambda point.

00:59:14.262 --> 00:59:17.006
I have already mentioned
that liquid helium has

00:59:17.006 --> 00:59:20.250
a remarkably small
[INAUDIBLE] vaporization,

00:59:20.250 --> 00:59:23.244
only five calories per gram.

00:59:23.244 --> 00:59:26.737
At the same time, liquid
helium at 4.2 degrees

00:59:26.737 --> 00:59:31.750
has a high specific heat,
almost calorie per gram.

00:59:31.750 --> 00:59:34.355
Therefore, 1 gram of
the vapor pumped away

00:59:34.355 --> 00:59:36.830
carries with it
an amount of heat

00:59:36.830 --> 00:59:42.230
which can cool only 5 or 6 grams
of liquid helium by 1 degree.

00:59:42.230 --> 00:59:44.460
That's not very much cooling.

00:59:44.460 --> 00:59:46.930
It is less by a
factor of almost 100

00:59:46.930 --> 00:59:51.110
than when we cool
water by evaporation.

00:59:51.110 --> 00:59:53.710
The situation gets even
worse as cooling progresses

00:59:53.710 --> 00:59:57.588
below 4.2 degrees because the
specific heat of liquid helium

00:59:57.588 --> 01:00:00.570
rises astonishingly.

01:00:00.570 --> 01:00:05.280
As we approach 2,17
degrees, the lambda point.

01:00:05.280 --> 01:00:07.440
The heat of vaporization,
on the other hand,

01:00:07.440 --> 01:00:10.190
remains roughly the same.

01:00:10.190 --> 01:00:12.460
So a given amount
of vapor carried

01:00:12.460 --> 01:00:14.960
off produces less
and less cooling

01:00:14.960 --> 01:00:20.240
as we approach 2.17 degrees,

01:00:20.240 --> 01:00:23.130
Our thermometer here
is a low pressure gauge

01:00:23.130 --> 01:00:26.520
connected to the space
above the liquid helium.

01:00:26.520 --> 01:00:29.272
The needle registers
the pressure there.

01:00:29.272 --> 01:00:33.240
It is the saturated vapor
pressure of liquid helium.

01:00:33.240 --> 01:00:37.430
The gauge is calibrated for
the corresponding temperature.

01:00:37.430 --> 01:00:41.412
We call it a vapor
pressure thermometer.

01:00:41.412 --> 01:00:43.620
As we approach 2.17
degrees, boiling

01:00:43.620 --> 01:00:44.885
becomes increasingly violent.

01:00:48.662 --> 01:00:51.142
Suddenly it stops.

01:00:51.142 --> 01:00:55.120
This was the transition.

01:00:55.120 --> 01:00:57.732
The liquid you now
see is helium II.

01:00:57.732 --> 01:01:02.500
Even though evaporation does
continue, there is no boiling.

01:01:02.500 --> 01:01:06.309
The normal liquids, such
as the water in this basin,

01:01:06.309 --> 01:01:10.660
boil because of their relatively
low heat conductivity.

01:01:10.660 --> 01:01:13.199
Before heat,
[INAUDIBLE] at one point

01:01:13.199 --> 01:01:15.075
can be carried away
to a cooler place

01:01:15.075 --> 01:01:19.300
in the liquid bubbles
of the vapor form.

01:01:19.300 --> 01:01:23.390
Helium I behaves like a
normal liquid in this respect.

01:01:23.390 --> 01:01:25.470
The absence of
boiling in helium II

01:01:25.470 --> 01:01:27.790
reveals that this
phase acts as if it

01:01:27.790 --> 01:01:31.546
had a large heat conductivity.

01:01:31.546 --> 01:01:34.844
As a matter of fact, as
the liquid helium passed

01:01:34.844 --> 01:01:36.302
through the lambda
point transition

01:01:36.302 --> 01:01:38.926
you just saw, its
heat conductivity

01:01:38.926 --> 01:01:41.290
increased by the fantastic
factor of one million.

01:01:43.880 --> 01:01:47.340
The heat conductivity of
helium II is many times

01:01:47.340 --> 01:01:50.270
greater than in the
metals silver and copper,

01:01:50.270 --> 01:01:52.870
which are among the best
solid heat conductors.

01:01:52.870 --> 01:01:55.265
And yet here we
deal with a liquid.

01:01:55.265 --> 01:01:57.220
For this alone,
helium II deserves

01:01:57.220 --> 01:01:59.500
the name of superfluid.

01:01:59.500 --> 01:02:02.610
Actually, the way in
which helium II transports

01:02:02.610 --> 01:02:05.304
such large quantities
of heat so rapidly

01:02:05.304 --> 01:02:08.750
is totally different from
the classical concept

01:02:08.750 --> 01:02:11.040
for heat conduction.

01:02:11.040 --> 01:02:12.550
I'll come back to
the subject later

01:02:12.550 --> 01:02:15.440
in connection with an
experiment demonstrating

01:02:15.440 --> 01:02:20.260
the phenomenon of second
sound in helium II.

01:02:20.260 --> 01:02:23.710
Remember that this great
change in heat conductivity

01:02:23.710 --> 01:02:26.880
occurred at a single
and fixed transition

01:02:26.880 --> 01:02:29.246
temperature, the lambda point.

01:02:29.246 --> 01:02:32.630
We do indeed deal with
a change in phase,

01:02:32.630 --> 01:02:38.440
only here it is a change from
one liquid to another liquid.

01:02:38.440 --> 01:02:42.050
As we told you before, the
specific heat of liquid helium

01:02:42.050 --> 01:02:44.590
is very large as a lambda point.

01:02:44.590 --> 01:02:48.900
In fact, it behaves abnormally
even below the lambda point

01:02:48.900 --> 01:02:53.280
and falls again very rapidly
with the temperature.

01:02:53.280 --> 01:02:55.880
This discontinuity
in specific heat

01:02:55.880 --> 01:02:57.570
is another reflection
of the fact

01:02:57.570 --> 01:02:59.440
that we are dealing
with a change

01:02:59.440 --> 01:03:01.720
in the phase of the substance.

01:03:01.720 --> 01:03:05.415
By the way, the curve resembles
the Greek letter lambda.

01:03:05.415 --> 01:03:07.760
The transition
temperature got its name

01:03:07.760 --> 01:03:08.970
from the shape of this curve.

01:03:12.881 --> 01:03:14.370
[INAUDIBLE]

01:03:14.370 --> 01:03:19.200
The next one has to do with
the viscosity of liquid helium.

01:03:19.200 --> 01:03:21.285
When a normal liquid
flows through a tube,

01:03:21.285 --> 01:03:23.270
it will resist the flow.

01:03:23.270 --> 01:03:26.460
In this experiment, we
shall cause some glycerin

01:03:26.460 --> 01:03:29.800
to flow to a tube
under its own weight.

01:03:29.800 --> 01:03:32.043
The top layer is
colored glycerin.

01:03:36.960 --> 01:03:41.140
The liquid layer closest to
the tube wall adheres to it.

01:03:41.140 --> 01:03:45.040
The layer next in from the one
touching the wall flows by it

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:49.530
and is retarded as it flows due
to the interatomic, the van der

01:03:49.530 --> 01:03:51.850
Waals force of attraction.

01:03:51.850 --> 01:03:54.930
The second layer in
turn drags on the third,

01:03:54.930 --> 01:03:59.260
and so on inward from the
wall, producing fluid friction,

01:03:59.260 --> 01:03:59.820
or viscosity.

01:04:07.770 --> 01:04:09.910
The narrower the
tube, the slower

01:04:09.910 --> 01:04:11.972
the liquid rate
of flow through it

01:04:11.972 --> 01:04:14.750
under a given head of pressure.

01:04:14.750 --> 01:04:17.680
Here I have a beaker with
an unglazed ceramic bottom

01:04:17.680 --> 01:04:21.600
of ultra-fine [INAUDIBLE].

01:04:21.600 --> 01:04:24.420
Many capillary channels run
through this ceramic disk.

01:04:24.420 --> 01:04:28.360
The diameter is quite small,
about one micron which is

01:04:28.360 --> 01:04:32.390
1/10,000 of a centimeter.

01:04:32.390 --> 01:04:34.410
There is liquid
helium in the beaker.

01:04:34.410 --> 01:04:39.611
It is 4.2 degrees Kelvin,
helium I, the normal phase.

01:04:39.611 --> 01:04:41.916
The capillaries in the
disk are fine enough

01:04:41.916 --> 01:04:44.845
to prevent the liquid now in
the beaker from flowing through

01:04:44.845 --> 01:04:46.930
under its on weight.

01:04:46.930 --> 01:04:49.750
Clearly, helium I is viscous.

01:04:49.750 --> 01:04:52.730
To be sure, its
viscosity is very small.

01:04:52.730 --> 01:04:55.210
That's why we had to choose
extremely fine capillaries

01:04:55.210 --> 01:04:56.584
to demonstrate it.

01:05:00.560 --> 01:05:04.110
Here you see the lambda
point transition.

01:05:08.770 --> 01:05:11.700
The helium II all poured out.

01:05:11.700 --> 01:05:15.070
The rate of pouring would
not be noticeably slower

01:05:15.070 --> 01:05:18.770
if the [INAUDIBLE]
were made yet finer.

01:05:18.770 --> 01:05:20.938
We call this kind
of flow a superflow.

01:05:24.842 --> 01:05:30.220
The temperature is
now at 1.6 degrees.

01:05:30.220 --> 01:05:33.304
The superflow is even faster.

01:05:33.304 --> 01:05:36.200
The viscosity of helium
II in this experiment

01:05:36.200 --> 01:05:38.532
is so small that it has
not been possible to find

01:05:38.532 --> 01:05:40.620
a value for it.

01:05:40.620 --> 01:05:43.990
It is less than the experimental
uncertainty incurred

01:05:43.990 --> 01:05:46.760
in attempts to measure it.

01:05:46.760 --> 01:05:50.064
We now believe that
helium II, the superfluid,

01:05:50.064 --> 01:05:54.306
has zero viscosity, although
we should be more precise here.

01:05:54.306 --> 01:06:00.675
We believe its viscosity is zero
when observing capillary flow.

01:06:00.675 --> 01:06:03.280
Bear this statement
in mind, for we

01:06:03.280 --> 01:06:05.720
will come up with a
contradiction to it

01:06:05.720 --> 01:06:07.916
in the next experiment,
where we will

01:06:07.916 --> 01:06:11.576
look for viscosity by
a different method.

01:06:11.576 --> 01:06:14.016
There is a copper cylinder
in the liquid helium,

01:06:14.016 --> 01:06:18.896
so mounted as we can turn
it about a vertical axis.

01:06:18.896 --> 01:06:22.090
In order to turn it smoothly
and with as little vibration as

01:06:22.090 --> 01:06:25.110
possible, we laid the
cylinder into the [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:25.110 --> 01:06:27.542
of a simple induction
motor energized

01:06:27.542 --> 01:06:29.024
from outside the dewar.

01:06:29.024 --> 01:06:31.494
The four horizontal
coils you see

01:06:31.494 --> 01:06:34.458
provide the torque which
turns the cylinder.

01:06:34.458 --> 01:06:37.230
The liquid helium is
electrically non-conducting.

01:06:37.230 --> 01:06:40.410
The coil exerts no
torque on it directly.

01:06:40.410 --> 01:06:44.350
Yet as we turn on our
motor, the liquid layer

01:06:44.350 --> 01:06:47.048
bounding the cylinder is
dragged along behind it.

01:06:47.048 --> 01:06:50.280
The boundary layer in turn
drags on the next layer,

01:06:50.280 --> 01:06:51.310
and so on outward.

01:06:58.955 --> 01:07:01.640
Finally a circulation
showing up in the helium

01:07:01.640 --> 01:07:05.432
due to its own viscosity and
the wooden panels we [INAUDIBLE]

01:07:05.432 --> 01:07:06.358
is turned along.

01:07:08.987 --> 01:07:10.820
What we have just seen
occurred in helium I,

01:07:10.820 --> 01:07:15.290
the normal phase at
4.2 degrees Kelvin.

01:07:15.290 --> 01:07:17.952
That is to say,
this demonstration

01:07:17.952 --> 01:07:22.470
is consistent with our results
for helium I by capillary flow.

01:07:22.470 --> 01:07:26.254
Helium I is viscous.

01:07:26.254 --> 01:07:28.470
Here you see the liquid
cooled down and passing

01:07:28.470 --> 01:07:30.400
into the superfluid
phase, helium II.

01:07:42.960 --> 01:07:44.020
Let's turn on the motor.

01:07:55.428 --> 01:07:58.404
The paddle wheel starts again.

01:07:58.404 --> 01:08:01.248
What does this mean?

01:08:01.248 --> 01:08:04.980
First of all, let me
emphasize that, like helium I,

01:08:04.980 --> 01:08:08.560
helium II is also non-conducting
in the electrical sense.

01:08:08.560 --> 01:08:10.710
In other words, the
circulation in the experiment

01:08:10.710 --> 01:08:15.910
can only have been caused
through viscous drag.

01:08:15.910 --> 01:08:19.250
So we conclude from the
rotating cylinder observations

01:08:19.250 --> 01:08:22.499
that helium II is viscous
and from the method

01:08:22.499 --> 01:08:26.370
of capillary flow that
it has zero viscosity.

01:08:26.370 --> 01:08:29.649
Our experimentation has
come up with a paradox.

01:08:29.649 --> 01:08:32.415
No normal classical
liquid is known

01:08:32.415 --> 01:08:35.860
to behave so inconsistently, in
capillary flow on the one hand

01:08:35.860 --> 01:08:39.158
and in bulk flow on the other.

01:08:39.158 --> 01:08:42.180
This state of affairs
forces us to think

01:08:42.180 --> 01:08:46.560
of helium II, the
superfluid, not as a single,

01:08:46.560 --> 01:08:48.996
but as a dual liquid.

01:08:48.996 --> 01:08:52.390
It appeared as if helium
II had two separate and yet

01:08:52.390 --> 01:08:54.817
interpenetrating
component liquids.

01:08:54.817 --> 01:08:56.813
We shall call one
component normal.

01:08:56.813 --> 01:09:00.306
It is this component
which we call

01:09:00.306 --> 01:09:02.240
responsible for the
appearance of viscosity

01:09:02.240 --> 01:09:05.565
below the lambda point in the
rotating cylinder experiment.

01:09:05.565 --> 01:09:09.016
The normal component,
as the name suggests,

01:09:09.016 --> 01:09:14.439
behaves like a normal liquid,
and therefore as viscosity.

01:09:14.439 --> 01:09:17.910
It is the one which the cylinder
drags along as its turned.

01:09:17.910 --> 01:09:20.910
But the normal components
cannot flow through the narrow

01:09:20.910 --> 01:09:25.410
channels of the ceramic disc
because of its viscosity.

01:09:25.410 --> 01:09:28.410
The second component
has zero viscosity,

01:09:28.410 --> 01:09:30.910
and it's called the
superfluid component.

01:09:30.910 --> 01:09:33.910
We think that it does
not participate at all

01:09:33.910 --> 01:09:36.810
in the rotating cylinder
experiment below the lambda

01:09:36.810 --> 01:09:37.639
point.

01:09:37.639 --> 01:09:40.034
It stays at rest.

01:09:40.034 --> 01:09:43.546
On the other hand, it can flow
through channels of one micron

01:09:43.546 --> 01:09:45.864
diameter with the greatest
of ease and countering

01:09:45.864 --> 01:09:50.834
no resistance whatever
because it has no viscosity.

01:09:50.834 --> 01:09:53.819
As we'll see later, this
flow is not repeated even

01:09:53.819 --> 01:09:56.070
when the capillary
diameters are made

01:09:56.070 --> 01:09:58.720
far smaller than one micron.

01:09:58.720 --> 01:10:01.822
This [INAUDIBLE] construction
is called the two fluid

01:10:01.822 --> 01:10:04.237
model for liquid helium II.

01:10:04.237 --> 01:10:05.927
Whether it is correct
or not depends

01:10:05.927 --> 01:10:08.190
on further tests
comparing the theory

01:10:08.190 --> 01:10:13.750
based on this model with
experimental results.

01:10:13.750 --> 01:10:17.120
We now go on to another
phenomenon, the fountain

01:10:17.120 --> 01:10:17.620
effect.

01:10:17.620 --> 01:10:20.470
What you see here
is a tube which

01:10:20.470 --> 01:10:23.125
narrows down and then
opens into a bulb.

01:10:23.125 --> 01:10:26.240
A small piece of cotton is
stuffed into the [INAUDIBLE]

01:10:26.240 --> 01:10:27.930
section between the
tube and the bulb.

01:10:27.930 --> 01:10:31.311
And the bulb has been tightly
packed with one of the finest

01:10:31.311 --> 01:10:35.660
powders available, [INAUDIBLE].

01:10:35.660 --> 01:10:39.388
And second wad of cotton
keeps the powder in the bulb.

01:10:39.388 --> 01:10:44.278
This powder presents extremely
fine capillary channels.

01:10:44.278 --> 01:10:47.020
Their average diameter is a
small fraction of 1 micron.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:53.590
This device has been
placed in the dewar.

01:10:53.590 --> 01:10:57.590
The liquid helium is
below the lambda point.

01:10:57.590 --> 01:11:01.110
We submerge the bulb, and then
we'll send a beam of light

01:11:01.110 --> 01:11:05.610
from this lamp to a
point near the top.

01:11:05.610 --> 01:11:09.375
You will see the light beam
when the lamp is turned on.

01:11:09.375 --> 01:11:13.080
It focuses some heat in the
form of infrared radiation

01:11:13.080 --> 01:11:15.000
on the point in question.

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:17.880
The temperature will rise
above the temperature

01:11:17.880 --> 01:11:20.760
of the rest of the apparatus.

01:11:20.760 --> 01:11:21.720
Let us turn it on.

01:11:29.600 --> 01:11:33.102
Liquid helium flows through the
hole in the bottom of the bulb,

01:11:33.102 --> 01:11:35.940
through the fine
powder, and rises

01:11:35.940 --> 01:11:38.310
above the level of
liquid helium outside.

01:11:38.310 --> 01:11:40.225
The height to which
it will go depends

01:11:40.225 --> 01:11:42.205
on the temperature
increase produced

01:11:42.205 --> 01:11:45.700
bu the lamp focused on the bulb.

01:11:45.700 --> 01:11:48.422
We can very well ask, where
does the mechanical energy

01:11:48.422 --> 01:11:51.866
come from that does the
work necessary to pump

01:11:51.866 --> 01:11:55.310
the liquid above
the ambient level?

01:11:55.310 --> 01:11:57.662
Before we attempt to
discuss this question,

01:11:57.662 --> 01:12:00.690
there are two other facts
that should be noted.

01:12:00.690 --> 01:12:03.780
The first is by now obvious.

01:12:03.780 --> 01:12:07.780
The upward flow through the bulb
must clearly be a superfluid.

01:12:07.780 --> 01:12:13.280
Only the superfluid component
of helium II could get through.

01:12:13.280 --> 01:12:15.780
The second fact is
more significant.

01:12:15.780 --> 01:12:19.700
Let me explain it this way, the
superfluid flows spontaneously

01:12:19.700 --> 01:12:23.440
from a to b,from a
cooler to a warmer place.

01:12:23.440 --> 01:12:25.970
Point a is in the
cold liquid, but b

01:12:25.970 --> 01:12:28.139
is being heated
with infrared rays.

01:12:28.139 --> 01:12:32.576
The second law of thermodynamics
positively says that heat

01:12:32.576 --> 01:12:36.273
cannot of itself flow from
a point of lower to a point

01:12:36.273 --> 01:12:38.492
of higher temperature.

01:12:38.492 --> 01:12:40.628
What does this mean
to us here, knowing

01:12:40.628 --> 01:12:42.436
as we do that the
superfluid is flowing

01:12:42.436 --> 01:12:45.790
from a colder to a warmer spot?

01:12:45.790 --> 01:12:51.272
Simply this, it carries no
heat, no thermal energy.

01:12:51.272 --> 01:12:55.060
Any internal energy
[INAUDIBLE] is no longer

01:12:55.060 --> 01:12:56.964
thermally available.

01:12:56.964 --> 01:13:01.724
To say it precisely,
it has zero entropy.

01:13:01.724 --> 01:13:03.730
We have discovered another
remarkable property

01:13:03.730 --> 01:13:05.248
of helium II.

01:13:05.248 --> 01:13:09.072
Its superfluid component
not only is friction free,

01:13:09.072 --> 01:13:11.940
it also contains no heat.

01:13:11.940 --> 01:13:13.852
The heat energy
contained in helium II

01:13:13.852 --> 01:13:19.595
as a whole resides, all of
it, in the normal component.

01:13:19.595 --> 01:13:23.060
We may, of course, add heat
to the superfluid component,

01:13:23.060 --> 01:13:27.030
as we are doing when it passes
the spot heated by the lamp.

01:13:27.030 --> 01:13:28.910
But in doing so, we
are converting it

01:13:28.910 --> 01:13:32.908
into the normal component.

01:13:32.908 --> 01:13:36.360
Let me return briefly to
a question posed earlier.

01:13:36.360 --> 01:13:38.808
Mechanical work is done
in pumping the liquid

01:13:38.808 --> 01:13:40.804
above equilibrium level.

01:13:40.804 --> 01:13:42.800
Where does it come from?

01:13:42.800 --> 01:13:45.295
I cannot answer this
question here in full,

01:13:45.295 --> 01:13:49.287
but it suffice to tell you that
we are dealing here with a heat

01:13:49.287 --> 01:13:49.800
engine.

01:13:49.800 --> 01:13:51.508
The mechanical energy
comes from the heat

01:13:51.508 --> 01:13:54.304
added at the light spot.

01:13:54.304 --> 01:13:57.400
An amusing demonstration
of the same phenomenon

01:13:57.400 --> 01:14:00.522
again uses a bulb
packed with rouge,

01:14:00.522 --> 01:14:03.994
but this one opens
into a capillary.

01:14:03.994 --> 01:14:07.962
Light is beamed on a spot
just below the capillary,

01:14:07.962 --> 01:14:09.610
and it produces a
helium fountain.

01:14:14.273 --> 01:14:17.195
The phenomenon in this and
the previous experiment

01:14:17.195 --> 01:14:19.143
has become known as
the thermomechanical,

01:14:19.143 --> 01:14:23.526
or the fountain, effect.

01:14:23.526 --> 01:14:27.160
Below the lambda point,
the superfluid component

01:14:27.160 --> 01:14:29.980
of liquid helium creeps
up along the walls

01:14:29.980 --> 01:14:32.758
of its container in an
extremely thin film.

01:14:32.758 --> 01:14:34.740
It is known as a Rollin film.

01:14:37.674 --> 01:14:41.586
This creeping film is
a variety of superflow.

01:14:41.586 --> 01:14:45.752
It is difficult to make the film
itself directly visible to you.

01:14:45.752 --> 01:14:49.215
To show it indirectly,
we've put some liquid helium

01:14:49.215 --> 01:14:51.370
into a glass vessel.

01:14:51.370 --> 01:14:54.360
It is below the lambda point.

01:14:54.360 --> 01:14:57.140
There is no part porous
bottom in this vessel.

01:14:57.140 --> 01:14:59.920
The film rises along
the inside wall

01:14:59.920 --> 01:15:01.310
and comes down
along the outside,

01:15:01.310 --> 01:15:03.880
collecting in drops
at the bottom.

01:15:03.880 --> 01:15:06.265
The thickness of
this creeping film

01:15:06.265 --> 01:15:09.604
is only a small fraction of
1 micron and of the order

01:15:09.604 --> 01:15:12.480
of 200 to 300 angstrom.

01:15:12.480 --> 01:15:16.512
Its speed, while small just
below the lambda point,

01:15:16.512 --> 01:15:18.902
may reach a value as
high as 35 centimeters

01:15:18.902 --> 01:15:22.815
per second at
lower temperatures.

01:15:22.815 --> 01:15:27.120
Our next experiment deals with
the phenomenon of second sound.

01:15:27.120 --> 01:15:29.915
We are all familiar with wave
motion in elastic materials,

01:15:29.915 --> 01:15:34.120
be they solids,
liquids, or gases.

01:15:34.120 --> 01:15:37.630
Elastic energy of deformation,
carried away from its source

01:15:37.630 --> 01:15:40.690
in the form of waves with
a characteristic speed,

01:15:40.690 --> 01:15:43.842
the speed of sound.

01:15:43.842 --> 01:15:45.600
Liquid helium is an
elastic substance

01:15:45.600 --> 01:15:48.320
both above and below
the lambda point.

01:15:48.320 --> 01:15:51.300
Both helium one and two
support sound waves.

01:15:51.300 --> 01:15:54.640
Now helium II, the
superfluid phase,

01:15:54.640 --> 01:15:57.650
also conducts heat
in the form of waves.

01:15:57.650 --> 01:16:01.580
This remarkable property is
shared by no other substance.

01:16:01.580 --> 01:16:06.593
For better or for worse, it
has been called second sound.

01:16:06.593 --> 01:16:09.540
Normal heat conduction
is a diffusion process.

01:16:09.540 --> 01:16:12.400
The rate of flow of heat is
proportional to the temperature

01:16:12.400 --> 01:16:13.310
differences.

01:16:13.310 --> 01:16:18.104
But in helium II it
is a wave process.

01:16:18.104 --> 01:16:23.170
Heat flows through helium II
with a characteristic speed,

01:16:23.170 --> 01:16:26.210
the speed of second sound.

01:16:26.210 --> 01:16:30.360
We shall send small heat pulses
into helium II from a heater.

01:16:30.360 --> 01:16:32.682
They will spread away
from the heater uniformly,

01:16:32.682 --> 01:16:34.140
carrying the heat
energy with them.

01:16:39.712 --> 01:16:41.337
The speed of second
sound is small just

01:16:41.337 --> 01:16:43.960
below the lambda point.

01:16:43.960 --> 01:16:46.420
In the neighborhood
of 1.6 degrees Kelvin,

01:16:46.420 --> 01:16:49.210
it reaches a value of
roughly 20 meters per second,

01:16:49.210 --> 01:16:54.010
and it is in this range that
we will run our demonstration.

01:16:54.010 --> 01:16:57.142
The experimental
procedure is as follows.

01:16:57.142 --> 01:17:01.081
There are two disks
in the liquid helium.

01:17:01.081 --> 01:17:04.490
They are carbon resistors
with the carbon applied

01:17:04.490 --> 01:17:06.925
in thin layers on one
side of each disk.

01:17:06.925 --> 01:17:09.360
In this way, good
thermal contact

01:17:09.360 --> 01:17:13.256
is established between the
resistor and the liquid helium.

01:17:13.256 --> 01:17:15.920
The following resistor
will be used as a heater.

01:17:15.920 --> 01:17:18.580
Electric currents will
be sent through it

01:17:18.580 --> 01:17:22.435
in pulses from this pulse
generator by means of the cable

01:17:22.435 --> 01:17:24.295
you see here.

01:17:24.295 --> 01:17:26.620
The [INAUDIBLE] of
the generator is also

01:17:26.620 --> 01:17:31.490
connected via a second cable
to a dual-trace oscilloscope,

01:17:31.490 --> 01:17:34.760
where it will be recorded
on the bottom [? trip. ?]

01:17:34.760 --> 01:17:37.951
In other words, it will record
the heat pulse as it enters

01:17:37.951 --> 01:17:41.220
the liquid helium.

01:17:41.220 --> 01:17:43.790
The pulses have been turned on.

01:17:43.790 --> 01:17:45.770
They themselves trigger
the horizontal sweep

01:17:45.770 --> 01:17:50.214
of [INAUDIBLE], which
records [INAUDIBLE].

01:17:50.214 --> 01:17:53.060
It is calibrated
at 1 millisecond

01:17:53.060 --> 01:17:54.785
per unit on the scale.

01:17:54.785 --> 01:17:58.330
The pulses are 1
millisecond long.

01:17:58.330 --> 01:18:00.185
The pulses leave the
heater at the bottom

01:18:00.185 --> 01:18:02.420
in the form of
second sound and move

01:18:02.420 --> 01:18:05.790
up to where they strike the
carbon resistor at the top.

01:18:05.790 --> 01:18:10.375
Being heat pulses, they
greatly raise is temperature.

01:18:10.375 --> 01:18:13.550
The carbon resistor is
quite sensitive to changes

01:18:13.550 --> 01:18:14.175
in temperature.

01:18:14.175 --> 01:18:17.590
It acts as a thermometer.

01:18:17.590 --> 01:18:19.480
So the heat pulse
of second sound

01:18:19.480 --> 01:18:21.582
creates a pulse-like
change in the resistance

01:18:21.582 --> 01:18:24.300
of the [INAUDIBLE] up here.

01:18:24.300 --> 01:18:26.410
It isn't hard to
convert this resistance

01:18:26.410 --> 01:18:28.200
pulse into a [INAUDIBLE].

01:18:28.200 --> 01:18:31.260
What we will do is to
maintain a small DC

01:18:31.260 --> 01:18:33.211
current in the top resistor.

01:18:33.211 --> 01:18:36.650
It is supplied from a
battery in this metal box.

01:18:36.650 --> 01:18:38.757
The box shields the
circuits in order

01:18:38.757 --> 01:18:41.619
to reduce electronic noise.

01:18:41.619 --> 01:18:44.004
The voltage pulse is small.

01:18:44.004 --> 01:18:50.080
In this second box
we have an amplifier.

01:18:50.080 --> 01:18:53.527
The amplified output is fed
into the oscilloscope, where

01:18:53.527 --> 01:18:55.660
it will appear on
the upper trace.

01:18:55.660 --> 01:18:57.556
The horizontal
timescale on this trace

01:18:57.556 --> 01:19:00.860
is exactly the same as
for the bottom trace.

01:19:00.860 --> 01:19:03.710
However, the upper trace
records both exchanges

01:19:03.710 --> 01:19:06.520
as they occur in
the top resistor,

01:19:06.520 --> 01:19:09.852
a detector of second sound.

01:19:09.852 --> 01:19:36.172
The temperature of the liquid
is about 1.65 degrees Kelvin.

01:19:36.172 --> 01:19:42.110
The battery has been turned
on, and now the amplifier.

01:19:42.110 --> 01:19:45.515
Among noise and other
distortions in the upper trace,

01:19:45.515 --> 01:19:49.760
a clear-cut voltage pulse
appears about 4 and 1/2 units

01:19:49.760 --> 01:19:53.100
to the right, 4 and
1/2 milliseconds later

01:19:53.100 --> 01:19:57.687
than the pulse
entering the heater.

01:19:57.687 --> 01:20:02.724
This pulse in the upper trace is
also about 1 millisecond long.

01:20:02.724 --> 01:20:07.188
It is the second sound as it
arrives at the upper resistor.

01:20:07.188 --> 01:20:10.164
The upper trace also shows
a strong voltage pulse

01:20:10.164 --> 01:20:13.636
at the left, simultaneous
to the heater pulse.

01:20:13.636 --> 01:20:16.612
That's due to pick-up
by electromagnetic waves

01:20:16.612 --> 01:20:20.084
with the heater acting as
transmitter and the detector

01:20:20.084 --> 01:20:21.076
as receiver.

01:20:28.020 --> 01:20:30.996
We're moving the detector
toward the heater.

01:20:30.996 --> 01:20:33.476
The pulse moves
with it to the left.

01:20:33.476 --> 01:20:37.865
Notice the echos of second sound
which appear on the upper trace

01:20:37.865 --> 01:20:41.360
while the detector
is near the heater.

01:20:41.360 --> 01:20:44.270
They're caused by multiple
reflections between the two

01:20:44.270 --> 01:20:45.725
resistors.

01:20:45.725 --> 01:20:50.090
A total of three echos
is clearly visible.

01:20:50.090 --> 01:20:51.060
